The Treasury has allocated Sh2.2 billion to the Meteorological department, a few hours after experts suggested it be made a semiautonomous agency.Treasury CS Henry Rotich on Thursday said the government remains committed to mitigating the effects of climate change, having signed the protocol on climate change following the adoption of the Paris Agreement. Rotich, while presenting the 2017-2018 budget, said climate change measures will be mainstreamed into all government projects. On Wednesday, weather experts said the Met department would be able to release prompt, more accurate and better information on weather if it was semi-autonomous.Environment PS Charles Sunkuli said a policy and legal framework are awaiting Cabinet approval. He made the announcement after World Meteorological Organisation representative for Eastern and Southern Africa region Stephen Njoroge prevailed upon him. Njoroge told the PS all sectors are affected by weather and so accurate information is critical.